<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="s_bases_top">
  <title>Bases for topological spaces</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
    When defining a topology <m>\mathcal{T}</m> for a set <m>X</m> it is often convenient to specify instead a more manageable subset of <m> \mathcal{T}</m> that we can use to <em>generate</em> the entire topology using arbitrary unions and/or finite intersections (our open set operators). A <em>topological basis</em> is a particularly nice example of this (<xref ref="d_basis" text="global"/>) as the open sets of the topology it generates can be expressed as (arbitrary) unions of the basis elements. Bases will also provide a convenient way of comparing different topologies and (later on) determining whether relevant topological properties are satisfied by a given space.
    </p>
</introduction>
<definition xml:id="d_basis">
  <title>Topological basis</title>
  <statement>
    Let <m>X</m> be a set. A <term>(topological) basis</term> in <m>X</m> is a collection <m>\mathcal{B}</m> of subsets of <m>X</m> satisfying the following axioms:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <title>Covers <m>X</m></title>
        <p>
          For each <m>x\in X</m> there is a set <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Intersections covered by basis elements</title>
        <p>
          If <m>B_1, B_2\in \mathcal{B}</m>, then for all <m>x\in B_1\cap B_2</m> there is a <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B\subseteq B_1\cap B_2</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</definition>
  <remark xml:id="rm_alt_axiom2">
  <title>Equivalent alternative to axiom (2)</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Axiom (2) in <xref ref="d_basis"/> is equivalent to saying that <m>B_1\cap B_2</m> is equal to a union of elements of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. In other words, we could replace (2) with the equivalent statement
      <me>
        (2') \ B_1, B_2\in \mathcal{B}\implies B_1\cap B_2=\bigcup_{\alpha\in I} B_\alpha \text{ for some } B_\alpha\in \mathcal{B}
      </me>.
      This is a consequence of the following more general fact: let <m>U</m> be a subset of <m>X</m>, and let <m>\mathcal{A}</m> be a collection of subsets of <m>X</m>; we have <m>U=\bigcup_{i\in I} A_i</m> for some <m>A_i\in \mathcal{A}</m> if and only if for all <m>x\in U</m> there exists an element <m>A_x\in \mathcal{A}</m> such that <m>x\in A_x\subseteq U</m>. I'll leave the proof of this to you.
    </p>
  </statement>
</remark>

<example xml:id="eg_basis_R">
  <title>Some bases for <m>\R</m></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the given collections <m>\mathcal{B}</m> are bases in <m>\R</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_1=\{(x-\epsilon, x+\epsilon)\colon x,\epsilon\in \R, \epsilon&gt; 0\}=\{(a,b)\colon a,b\in\R, a&lt; b\}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_2=\{ (p,q)\colon p,q\in \Q, p&lt; q\} </m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_3=\{[a,b)\colon a,b\in \R, a&lt; b\}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      It is clear that each collection of interval types covers <m>\R</m> in the sense of axiom (1). As for axiom (2), for each <m>\mathcal{B}_i</m>, <m>1\leq i\leq 3</m>, note that intersection of these types of intervals are either empty, or another interval of the same type. This is a result of the fact that
      <md>
        <mrow> (a,b)\cap (c,d)\amp = \left(\max(a,c),\min(b,d)\right) </mrow>
        <mrow> [a,b)\cap [c,d) \amp = \left [\max{a,c}, \min(b,d)\right) </mrow>
      </md>,
      where the interval described on the right is understood to be the empty set if <m>\max(a,c)\geq \min(b,d)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="th_basis_generated">
  <title>Topology generated by basis</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{B}\subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a basis in the set <m>X</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p> The set
          <me>
            \mathcal{T}=\{U\subseteq X\colon U=\bigcup_{i\in I}B_i \text{ for some elements } B_i\in \mathcal{B}\}
          </me>
          is a topology on <m>X</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          We have the following alternate description of <m>\mathcal{T}</m>:
          <me>
            U\in \mathcal{T} \iff \text{ for all } x\in U \ \text{ there exists } B\in \mathcal{B} \text{ such that } x\in B\subseteq U
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Note: it is somewhat easier to show that <m>\mathcal{T}</m> is a topology using the description in statement (2), and then to show that the description in statement (1) is the same. (See Munkres for an approach like this.) I've decided to go the hard way since this is how I proceeded in class, and since it puts us through some useful set theory calisthenics!
  </p>
  <p>
    First we show that <m>\mathcal{T}</m> as defined in (1) is a topology. We treat each axiom separately.
  </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          The empty set is the <q>empty union</q> of elements of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>; thus <m>\emptyset\in \mathcal{T}</m>. The covering axiom for bases implies that for all <m>x\in X</m> there is a <m>B_x\in\mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B_x</m>. It follows that <m>X=\bigcup_{x\in X}B_x</m> is a union of elements of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>, and thus that <m>X\in \mathcal{T}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In plain English, a union of unions of elements of <m>\mathcal{B}</m> is a union of elements of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. More rigorously, assume we have a collection of <m>U_i\in \mathcal{T}</m>. By definition, for each <m>i\in I</m> we have <m>U_i=\bigcup_{j\in J_i} B_{i,j}</m>, where <m>B_{i,j}\in \mathcal{B}</m> for each <m>j\in J</m>. Thus
          <md>
            <mrow>\bigcup_{i\in I} U_i \amp = \bigcup_{i\in I}\bigcup_{j\in J_i} B_{i,j} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \bigcup_{(i,j)\in K} B_{i,j} </mrow>
          </md>,
          where <m>K</m> is the set of all pairs of the form <m>(i,j)</m> for <m>i\in I</m> and <m>j\in I_j</m>. Thus <m>U=\bigcup_{i\in I} U_i</m> is a union of basis elements, and hence an element of <m>\mathcal{T}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          It is enough to show that <m>U, V\in \mathcal{T}\implies U\cap V\in \mathcal{T}</m>. (See <xref ref="rm_def_top"/>.) Assume <m>U=\bigcup_{i\in I}B_i</m>, <m>V=\bigcup_{j\in J}B_j</m>, where <m>B_i, B_j\in \mathcal{B}</m> for all <m>i\in I, j\in J</m>. We have
          <md>
            <mrow>U\cap V \amp= \left(\bigcup_{i\in I}B_i \right) \cap \left( \bigcup_{j\in J}B_j\right) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \bigcup_{(i,j)\in I\times J} B_i\cap B_j </mrow>
          </md>.
          Now by axiom (2') for bases (see <xref ref="rm_alt_axiom2"/>), each <m>B_i\cap B_j</m> is a union of basis elements, and hence is an element <m>U_{i,j}\in \mathcal{T}</m>. We have already shown that <m>\mathcal{T}</m> is closed under arbitrary unions. Thus <m>U\cap V</m> is an element of <m>\mathcal{T}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      This shows that <m>\mathcal{T}</m>, as defined in statement (1) of the theorem, is a topology. Statement (2) now follows from the general claim made in <xref ref="rm_alt_axiom2"/>.
    </p>
  </proof>
</theorem>
<definition xml:id="d_basis_generated">
  <title>Topology generated by basis</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{B}\subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a basis in the set <m>X</m>. The topology
      <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_top_generated1">\mathcal{T}\amp =\{U\subseteq X\colon U=\bigcup_{i\in I}B_i \text{ for some elements } B_i\in \mathcal{B}\} </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_top_generated2">  \amp = \{U\subseteq X\colon \text{ for all } x\in U \text{ there exists } B\in \mathcal{B} \text{ s.t. } x\in B\subseteq U\}</mrow>
      </mdn>
      is called the <term>topology generated</term> by <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. Similarly, we call <m>\mathcal{B}</m> a basis for <m>\mathcal{T}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<theorem xml:id="th_compare_basis">
  <title>Comparing with bases</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{T}</m> be a topology on <m>X</m> generated by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> be a topology on <m>X</m>. We have
          <men xml:id="eq_compare_basis_top">
            \mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'\iff B\in \mathcal{T}' \text{ for all } B\in \mathcal{B}
          </men>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> be a topology on <m>X</m> generated by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}'</m>. We have
          <men xml:id="eq_compare_basis_basis">
            \mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'\iff \text{ for all } B\in \mathcal{B} \text{ and } x\in B  \text{ there exists } B'\in \mathcal{B}' \text{ s.t. } x\in B'\subseteq B
          </men>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</theorem>
<example xml:id="eg_basis_standard_R">
<title>A basis for the standard topology on <m>\R</m></title>
<statement>
  <p>
    Show that the <xref ref="top_eq_standard_R" text='custom'>standard topology on <m>\R</m> </xref> is topology generated by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}_1</m> in <xref ref="eg_basis_R"/>.
  </p>
</statement>
<solution>
  <p>
    Let <m>\mathcal{T}</m> be the topology generated by <m>\mathcal{B}_1</m> and let <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> be the <xref ref="top_eq_standard_R" text='custom'>standard topology on <m>\R</m> </xref>. Since every open interval is open in <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> each element of <m>\mathcal{B}_1</m> is an element of <m>\mathcal{T}'</m>. By <xref ref="eq_compare_basis_top"/>, we have <m>\mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'</m>.
    Next, assume <m>U\in\mathcal{T}'</m>; then by definition for all <m>x\in U</m> there exists <m>\epsilon_x&gt; 0</m> such that <m>(x-\epsilon_x, x+\epsilon_x)\subseteq U</m>. It follows that <m>U=\bigcup_{x\in U}(x-\epsilon_x, x+\epsilon_x)</m>, a union of elements of <m>\mathcal{B}_1</m>. Thus <m>U\in \mathcal{T}</m>, by <xref ref="eq_top_generated1"/>. This proves <m>\mathcal{T}'\subseteq \mathcal{T}</m>, and thus that <m>\mathcal{T}=\mathcal{T}'</m>, as desired.
  </p>
</solution>
</example>
<example xml:id="eg_multiple_bases_standard_R">
  <title>Multiple bases for the standard real topology</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the bases <m>\mathcal{B}_1, \mathcal{B}_2</m> from <xref ref="eg_basis_R"/> both generate the standard topology on <m>\R</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{T}_i</m> be the topology generated by <m>\mathcal{B}_i</m>, <m>1\leq i\leq 2</m>.
      We must show that <m>\mathcal{T}_1\subseteq \mathcal{T}_2</m> and <m>\mathcal{T}_2\subseteq \mathcal{T}_1</m>. Clearly any <m>(p,q)\in \mathcal{B}_2</m> is an element of <m>\mathcal{B}_1</m>, and hence an element of <m>\mathcal{T}_1</m>. It follows from <xref ref="eq_compare_basis_top"/> that <m>\mathcal{T}_2\subseteq \mathcal{T}_1</m>.
       Next, take any <m>(a,b)\in \mathcal{B}_1</m>. Since the rational numbers are dense in <m>\R</m>, for any <m>x\in (a,b)</m> we can find <m>p,q\in\R</m> satisfying <m>x\in (p,q)\subseteq (a,b)</m>. From <xref ref="eq_compare_basis_basis"/> it follows that <m>\mathcal{T}_1\subseteq \mathcal{T}_2</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
<project xml:id="top_eg_lower_limit">
  <title>Lower limit topology</title>
  <p>
    The collection <m>\mathcal{B}_l=\{([a,b)\colon a,b\in \R, a&lt; b\}</m> is called the <term>lower limit basis</term>, and the topology <m>\mathcal{T}_l</m> it generates is called the <term>lower limit topology</term>  on <m>\R</m>. We denote the topological space <m>(\R, \mathcal{T}_l)</m> as <m>\R_l</m>.
  </p>
</project>

