<theorem xml:id="th_basis_criterion">
  <title>Basis criterion</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{T}</m> be a topology on the set <m>X</m>. A subset <m>\mathcal{B}\subseteq \mathcal{T}</m> is a basis of <m>\mathcal{T}</m> if and only if for all <m>U\in \mathcal{T}</m> and <m>x\in U</m> there is an element <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B\subseteq U</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      We prove both implications of the given <q>if and only if</q> statement separately.
    </p>
    <case>
     <title>Case: <m>(\implies)</m></title>
    <p>
    Assume <m>\mathcal{T}</m> is generated by <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. According to the description of <m>\mathcal{T}</m> in <xref ref="eq_top_generated2"/>, for all <m>U\in \mathcal{T}</m> and <m>x\in U</m> there is an element <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B\subseteq U</m>.
    </p>
    </case>
    <case>
     <title>Case: <m>(\impliedby)</m></title>
    <p>
     Assume for that for all <m>U\in \mathcal{T}</m> and <m>x\in U</m> there is an element <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B\subseteq U</m>. Taking <m>U=X</m> we see in particular that for all <m>x\in X</m> there is a <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B</m>. Thus <m>\mathcal{B}</m> satisfies axiom (1) for a basis. Next, let <m>B_1, B_2\in \mathcal{B}</m> and take <m>x\in B_1\cap B_2</m>.
     Since <m>B_1, B_2\in \mathcal{T}</m> are open, so is <m>U=B_1\cap B_2</m>. Our assumption now implies that there is a <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B\subseteq U=B_1\cap B_2</m>. Thus axiom (2) of <xref ref="d_basis"/> holds, and we condlude <m>\mathcal{B}</m> is a basis.
    </p>
    </case>
  </proof>

</theorem>
