<!-- <p>
  <xref ref="d_basis_generated"/>, which speaks of a unique topology <em>generated</em> by a collection of subsets, will be justified retroactively by <xref ref="th_top_generated"/>.
</p> -->
<definition xml:id="d_top_generated">
  <title>Topology generated by a collection of subsets</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>X</m> be a set, and let <m>\mathcal{A}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a collection of subsets of <m>X</m>. The <term>topology generated</term> by <m>\mathcal{A}</m> is the coarsest topology <m>\mathcal{T}</m> on <m>X</m> containing <m>\mathcal{A}</m>. In more detail, <m>\mathcal{T}</m> is the unique topology on <m>X</m> satisfying the following:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\mathcal{A}\subseteq \mathcal{T}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> is a topology and <m>\mathcal{A}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'</m>, then <m>\mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>
<theorem xml:id="th_top_generated">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>X</m> be a set, and let <m>\mathcal{A}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a collection of subsets of <m>X</m>.
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            There is a unique topology <m>\mathcal{T}</m> generated by <m>\mathcal{A}</m> in the sense of <xref ref="d_top_generated"/>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            In fact, we have
            <men xml:id="eq_top_generated">
              \mathcal{T}=\bigcap_{\mathcal{T}'\in \operatorname{Top}}\mathcal{T}'
            </men>,
            where <m>\operatorname{Top}</m> is the collection of all topologies on <m>X</m> containing <m>\mathcal{A}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      First we show that there is <em>at most one</em> topology generated by <m>\mathcal{A}</m> in the sense of <xref ref="d_top_generated"/>. Indeed if <m>\mathcal{T}_1</m> and <m>\mathcal{T}_2</m> both satisfy the conditions of <xref ref="d_top_generated"/>, then both topologies contain <m>\mathcal{A}</m>; and since both topologies are the <em>coarsest</em> topologies satisfying this property, we have <m>\mathcal{T}_1\subseteq \mathcal{T}_2</m> and <m>\mathcal{T}_2\subseteq \mathcal{T}_1</m>. It follows that <m>\mathcal{T}_1=\mathcal{T}_2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Now we show that there is such a topology.
      Note first that the collection <m>\operatorname{Top}</m> is nonempty, since <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m> is a topology (the discrete topology) containing <m>\mathcal{A}</m>, and thus the intersection
      <men xml:id="proof_top_generated">
        \mathcal{T}=\bigcap_{\mathcal{T}'\in \operatorname{Top}}\mathcal{T}'
      </men>
      is nonempty. Now, by simple properties of intersection it follows that <m>\mathcal{T}</m>
      satisfies <m>\mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'</m> for any topology <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> containing <m>\mathcal{A}</m>. Furthermore, since <m>\mathcal{A}</m> is contained in <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> for all <m>\mathcal{T}'\in \operatorname{Top}</m>, it is also contained in <m>\mathcal{T}</m>, the intersection of the <m>\mathcal{T}'</m>. Thus the proof is complete if we can show that <m>\mathcal{T}</m> is in fact a topology. This in turn follows from the general fact that an intersection of topologies is a topology, the proof of which is left as an exercise.
    </p>
  </proof>
</theorem>




</section>
